    - By Default Angular Framework Supports Form Validations.
    - Angular framework stores the form related errors into "$error" object dynamically.

<form name = "myForm">
     <label>Uname.</label>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;
     <input type="text"
            name="uname"
            ng-minlength="3"
            ng-maxlength="6"
            required>

     <h5 ng-if="myForm.uname.$error.minlength">*** Minimum 3 Characters are required***</h5>
     <h5 ng-if="myForm.uname.$error.maxlength">*** Maximum 6 Characters Are Allowed***</h5>
     <h5 ng-if="myForm.uname.$error.required">*** Can't Left Blank***</h5>

    <br><br>
    <label>Email.</label>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;
    <input type="email"
           name="uemail"
           required>

    <h5 ng-if="myForm.uemail.$error.required">*** Can't Left Blank***</h5>
    <h5 ng-if="myForm.uemail.$error.email">*** Please Enter the Valid Email***</h5>

    <br><br>
    <label>Phone.</label>&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;
    <input type="text"
           name = "uphone"
           ng-pattern="/^\d{0,9}(\.\d{1,9})?$/"
           required>
    <h5 ng-if="myForm.uphone.$error.required">*** Can't Left Blank***</h5>
    <h5 ng-if="myForm.uphone.$error.pattern">*** Please Enter the Valid Phone Number***</h5>
</form>

Validations By Using ngMessages Module.

    - ngMessages is the Predefined Module in AngularJS.

    - By using ngMessages Module we can overcome the Data Redundency.


